      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the primary regulatory quantity for CPB device submissions. The model outputs RH directly via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation model integrated along streamlines. The QoI is fully relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry and cover the same operating conditions as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the subject device geometry. Operating conditions overlap with COU envelope. Validation activities are considered relevant. However, all validation experiments and simulations were conducted under steady-state Newtonian conditions, consistent with the simplified model; no pulsatile or non-Newtonian validation cases were included."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated by residual reduction of at least four orders of magnitude for all governing equations.",
      "rationale": "All steady-state simulations converged to residuals below 1e-5 for continuity and momentum, and 1e-6 for turbulence quantities. Mass imbalance across inlet/outlet boundaries is less than 0.01%. Solver error is negligible."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; qualitative review of analyst competency documentation is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, formal use-error assessment is not required. Lead analyst holds PhD in computational fluid dynamics with 8 years of rotary blood pump simulation experience. Peer review of simulation setup performed by independent senior engineer. Accepted without formal use-error study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing equations and turbulence closure are documented and justified for the flow regime; model form assumptions are stated.",
      "rationale": "The model employs steady-state Reynolds-Averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS) equations with the SST k-omega turbulence closure. Blood is modeled as a Newtonian fluid with constant viscosity (0.0035 Pa·s) and density (1056 kg/m³). The non-Newtonian shear-thinning behavior of blood and transient turbulent fluctuations are not represented; the model description notes these are handled via a simplified model. The SST k-omega closure is standard for rotating machinery applications and is considered adequate. No fidelity trade study was conducted to quantify the effect of Newtonian versus non-Newtonian rheology on the RH index prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model boundary conditions and material properties are specified with documented sources and uncertainty ranges.",
      "rationale": "Inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, rotational speed, and fluid properties are specified from experimental measurements and literature. Uncertainty in hematocrit (±2%) and viscosity (±5%) are documented. Boundary condition sensitivity study performed for inlet turbulence intensity (1%–5%); RH index sensitivity is less than 3%. Model inputs are adequately characterized for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; single experimental dataset from FDA benchmark study is accepted.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, statistical characterization of test sample variability is not required. A single experimental dataset from the FDA benchmark hemolysis study is used for validation. Sample-to-sample variability in bovine blood properties is acknowledged but not formally quantified."
    },
